{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17497077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17497077"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T09:03:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T09:03:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1468"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1468","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1468"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.05,0.11,0.23,0.55]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1468"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115625"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1468","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1468"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1468"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97628"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"766"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2956"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3086"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49168"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115625","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115625"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after an episode of abdominal pain. These episodes of pain occur at random times and certain foods seem to worsen his symptoms. His bowel habits fluctuate greatly with periods of diarrhoea followed by constipation. There is no mucous or blood in the stools, and he is otherwise well. He has had these symptoms intermittently over the last six months. His only medical condition is anxiety. On examination, he appears comfortable and his vital signs are all normal. His abdomen is soft but minimally tender throughout. As part of his work up, an abdominal X-ray is ordered (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"The X-ray shows changes consistent with which one of the following?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ureteric calculus","Perforation","Bowel ischaemia","Bowel obstruction","Situs inversus"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe stem describes a very common acute Emergency Department presentation of non-specific abdominal pain, likely in this case to reflect irritable bowel syndrome (after excluding all red flag causes). Regardless, an abdominal X-ray has been ordered which shows the gastric bubble present on the right side, rather than on the left as normal. This is a radiological diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Esitus inversus\u003C/strong\u003E; a rare condition where the abdominal viscera are all on the opposite side. It can also affect the heart and great vessels, which is labelled situs inversus totalis. It is very important diagnosis to make to avoid misdiagnosis of other conditions in future. There is no radiological evidence of any of the other listed pathological conditions of \u003Cstrong\u003Eureteric calculus\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eperforation\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eischaemia\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Eobstruction\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["When investigations are very abnormal, always consider rare causes"],"references":["Umar UKA, Alremeithi AN, Qayyum H. Incidental diagnosis of situs inversus totalis: a perspective from an emergency department attendance. BMJ Case Reports. 2021; 14(4)."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97628"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1468"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18387"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18387","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18387"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/b0ea3e4e-8d4d-4618-991d-8c6d9c8aabcd.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/b0ea3e4e-8d4d-4618-991d-8c6d9c8aabcd.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":613,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97628","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97628"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-24T17:36:55+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-24T17:37:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1468"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115625"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"766","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/766"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Situs inversus","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"